Timing-10am
Venue-Programming Lab 1
Pattern-5 marks program and 5 marks viva
Total marks-10
SyllabusObjects and Classes: Structure in C and C++, Class specification, Objects, Data hiding, Encapsulation and abstraction, namespaces, Array of objects, Passing objects as arguments, Returning object from a function, inline functions, Static data member and member function, ‘const’ member function.

Constructor and Destructor: Constructors, Parameterized Constructors, Constructor Overloading, Constructors in array of objects, Constructors with default arguments, Dynamic Initialization, Pointer to objects, this pointer, Dynamic memory allocation, Array of pointer to objects, Copy Constructor, Static objects, Friend function, and Friend classes

*Toast Talks* is the annual flagship event of Thapar Toastmasters Club, wherein we aim to provide a platform for every speaker to gain a prolific audience and showcase their true talent. 


It is time now, the _*REGISTRATION FORMS*_ for _*Toast Talks 7.0: 'The stage, words and you.'*_ are now out finally! 

Link: https://bit.ly/Toast-Talks-7
Dates: 7th, 8th, and 13th May.


🥂 *Day 1* would have the first round as a group event wherein we will pitch speakers within situations; the second round would be an individual event, but would be fairly simple, putting speakers’ wits to the test.

🥂 *Day 2* would comprise two individual events, and people who get screened after day 1 would be participating in the same.

🥂 *Day 3* would be the finale round. The ultimate test, to find out the best of the best.

Toast Talks 7.0 is the platform to proclaim who would be given the title of 🔊 _*BEST  PUBLIC SPEAKER ON CAMPUS*_ 🔊! Best of luck!

Regards,
Thapar Toastmasters Club

11/05/2022, 12:01 pm - Shreyya Saraf EEC: There's an element of truth we all seek every time we come across the forms of media around us. The mass media you consume defines how you decide on what's right and what's not. And in this field of news media, what determines the true story?

Owing to the news industry and its hold on how you perceive things, True Scoop is set to organize a digital news workshop in collaboration with ECHOES from 5 PM onwards on 11th May 2022 at Main Auditorium. Divisional Commissioner of Patiala, Mr. Chander Gaind (IAS), will be joining as the guest of honor. The workshop further comes with the promise of enlightening the crowd with the world of digital news and aims at being an interactive session as we explore the various dimensions of journalism. The workshop also gives an opportunity of earning an internship at True Scoop. 

Fill in the registrations forms as we gear up a workshop that discovers what media reflects and brings to this world: https://bit.ly/DigitalNewsWorkshop

Stay tuned to our Instagram handles for further updates!

*Project Description* - 

1. Analysis of circuits of various supercapacitors

2. Detailed overview of past work

3. Application of other present methods 

*This study intends to be published in peer review journal.*

*Benefits to be part of the study* 

1. Exposure to research ethics.
2. Improvement in manuscript writing skills.
3. Extensive knowledge about the field.
4. Will be beneficial for placements in core or R&D companies

*Who can join*

Students who have a good grasp of Network theory concepts (finding equivalent impedances)

22/05/2023, 5:39 pm - Mayan: Subject: Concerns Regarding Academic Pressure 
 I am writing to bring to your attention some pressing concerns that have been weighing heavily on the minds of students. It is with great respect and a sincere desire for positive change that I express these concerns on behalf of my fellow students.
First and foremost, I would like to address the issue of continuous evaluations. The excessive number of sessionals conducted per day, along with the expectation to prepare for three to four finals exams simultaneously, leaves students with minimal time to absorb and comprehend the course material effectively. This rigorous schedule not only hampers our ability to study but also prevents us from engaging in any meaningful extra-curricular activities or skill development initiatives.
Furthermore, the lack of holidays provided to adequately prepare for exams and sessionals is a matter of great concern. The absence of designated preparation days, coupled with ongoing classes, puts immense pressure on students to juggle multiple academic commitments. It is disheartening to note that while some branches are granted extended preparation leaves, others, like us, are deprived of the same privileges, resulting in an unbalanced grading system that is inequitable and unfair.
Another issue that needs urgent attention is the unavailability of study materials and delayed notification of MST and EST syllabus. Additionally, the lack of transparency regarding the weightage of EST and MST syllabi in the final exams leaves us uncertain about the criteria upon which our performance will be evaluated.
Moreover, the absence of holidays on Saturdays in the 5th semester of the 3rd year is a hindrance to our skill development and internship opportunities. Saturdays provide a valuable window for students to gain additional skills, explore internships, and engage in activities that enhance their prospects in the professional world. 
Lastly, I must emphasize the impact these demanding conditions are having on our mental health and overall well-being. The continuous evaluations, lack of breaks, and excessive workload contribute to elevated stress levels, leading to burnout and compromised performance. 
I implore you to consider the gravity of the situation and take prompt action to address these concerns. I have full faith in your commitment to our education and believe that with your intervention, positive changes can be implemented that will benefit the entire student community. 
Thank you

26/06/2023, 9:02 pm - Farooq: question 1
 You are given a binary string, and want to flip some bits of the string and find the maximum number of 1s which can be obtained. When flipping the bits, you have to pick an interval (i,j) for which the bits will not be flipped, while all other bits have to be flipped. You can pick only one such interval.

More formally, given a string input_str of length str_size that consists of only Os and 1s, choose two indices i and j such that 1 sis j< str_size and convert all Os to 1s and 1s to Os in the

interval [1, i] and [j, str_size]. Find the maximum number of 1s that can be obtained after performing the given operation. Note that this operation must be performed exactly once.

question 2
A tree is represented as an undirected connected graph of n nodes numbered from 1 to n and n- 1 edges. The ith edge connects the nodes numbered from edges[i][0] and edges[i][1] and each node iis associated with a value val[i],

In a special move, any node can be visited from any other node directly via teleportation.

Given val and edges, find the maximum sum of values of the nodes visited on a path starting and ending at node number 1 by using the special move at most once and visiting any edge at most once.

question 3 
Given an array arr of n integers that contains all the integers from 1 to n and an integer k, find the kth smallest MEX of a subarray of the array. That is, in a list containing MEX of all the subarrays, find the kth smallest integer.

The MEX of an array is the smallest positive integer not present in the array. For example, the MEX of [1, 2, 3] is 4 and that of [1, 3, 4, 5) is 2. A subarray is any contiguous segment of the array.

12/09/2023, 8:14 pm - Priyanshu: def getTime(s):
    # Write your code here
  n = len(s)
  time = 0
  current = 'A'
  for i in range(n):
    next = s[i]
    distance = ord(next) - ord(current)
    if distance < 0:
      distance += 26
    time += distance
    current = next
  return time
12/09/2023, 8:14 pm - Priyanshu: def balancedSum(arr):
   
    n = len(arr)
    
 
    total_sum = sum(arr)
    
   
    left_sum = 0
    
    for i in range(n):
        
        right_sum = total_sum - left_sum - arr[i]
        
        
        if left_sum == right_sum:
            return i
        
       
        left_sum += arr[i]
    
   
    return -1

The students may seek media attention for the issue.
The specific outcome of this situation will depend on a number of factors, including the severity of the teacher's conduct, the evidence that is available, and the university's response to the student complaints.

10/10/2023, 11:39 am - Vivek Garg EEC: import heapq

# Define the graph as an adjacency list
graph = {
    8: {(1, 0.5), (3, 0.75)},
    1: {(8, 0.5), (2, 0.45), (7, 0.35)},
    2: {(1, 0.45), (3, 1.5), (7, 1.25), (5, 2.5)},
    3: {(2, 1.5), (8, 0.75), (4, 0.75), (5, 0.25)},
    4: {(3, 0.75), (5, 0.25)},
    5: {(2, 2.5), (3, 0.25), (4, 0.25), (6, 0.8), (7, 1.5)},
    6: {(5, 0.8)},
    7: {(1, 0.35), (2, 1.25), (5, 1.5)}
}

# Best-First Search function
def best_first_search(start, goal):
    pq = [(0, start)]  # Priority queue with (cost, vertex) tuples
    cost_so_far = {start: 0}
    came_from = {}  # To track the parent nodes
    iteration = 0
    
    while pq:
        current_cost, current_vertex = heapq.heappop(pq)
        
        # Print the current state in each iteration
        print(f"Iteration {iteration}: Current Vertex = {current_vertex}, Current Cost = {current_cost}")
        iteration += 1
        
        # Check if we have reached the goal
        if current_vertex == goal:
            print("Goal reached with cost:", current_cost)
            
            # Reconstruct the path
            path = []
            while current_vertex is not None:
                path.append(current_vertex)
                current_vertex = came_from.get(current_vertex)
            path.reverse()
            print("Path taken:", " -> ".join(map(str, path)))
            
            return
        
        # Explore neighbors
        for neighbor_vertex, edge_cost in graph[current_vertex]:
            new_cost = current_cost + edge_cost
            
            # If we haven't visited this neighbor or found a better path, add it to the queue
            if neighbor_vertex not in cost_so_far or new_cost < cost_so_far[neighbor_vertex]:
                cost_so_far[neighbor_vertex] = new_cost
                came_from[neighbor_vertex] = current_vertex  # Record the parent
                heapq.heappush(pq, (new_cost, neighbor_vertex))
    
    # If we reach here, there's no path to the goal
    print("No path to the goal")

if _name_ == "_main_":
    start_vertex = 1
    goal_vertex = 6
    
    best_first_search(start_vertex, goal_vertex)

11/10/2023, 10:14 pm - Harsh Jha EEC: I am writing to bring to your attention a pressing concern regarding the quality and taste of the food being provided in our hostel. Over the past few weeks, several students, including myself, have noticed a significant decline in the quality of the meals served in the hostel's mess facility. 
The food lacks the basic taste and flavour that one would expect. It often tastes bland, overcooked, or under seasoned, making it unpalatable and unsatisfying. The food is low quality, tasteless, repetitive dishes and high waiting time to get food. The menu has become monotonous and lacks diversity. The limited options make it difficult for residents with dietary restrictions or preferences to find suitable meals. We believe that the quality of the food provided in the hostel is a vital aspect of our overall well-being. It directly affects our health, satisfaction, and overall living experience. We understand that there may be challenges in managing the dining facility, but we urge you to take immediate action to address these issues. Another issue is the absence of tandoor in our mess all the hostels including Q, D, C, B have tandoor. We are constantly served pulses (daal) and potato constantly for 5 days which have no to very bad taste and on complaining to mess manager no actions have been taken by them. We have to wait an unusually long time, approximately 5-10 minutes, just to get a simple item like chapati. It is disheartening to note that when we request fresh chapatis, we have been subjected to inappropriate behaviour and tantrums from the mess facility staff. Such unprofessional conduct not only adds to our dissatisfaction but also undermines the overall atmosphere in the hostel. Furthermore, the dining area where these are distributed is often overcrowded, and there is no proper distribution system for chapatis and parathas. This leads to a chaotic dining experience and adds to our dissatisfaction. Additionally, when the food is cooked and taste bad there is no feedback register in the mess and if there is we given various reasons by the mess manger and told not to write a review and when the food is cooked good epically on Friday we are specially told by the mess manger to write down reviews.
Sincerely,
Aryan Sharma

20/11/2023, 9:29 pm - Arun EEC: % Step 1: Define the dataset
% Input data (AND gate truth table)
X = [0 0; 0 1; 1 0; 1 1];
% Output data
Y = [0; 0; 0; 1];

% Step 2: Create a neural network
net = feedforwardnet(5); % Create a feedforward neural network with 5 hidden neurons
net = train(net, X', Y'); % Train the network using the dataset

% Step 3: Test the neural network
% Test input data
testX = [0 0; 0 1; 1 0; 1 1];
% Simulate the network to get output
output = net(testX');
output = round(output); % Round the output to the nearest integer (0 or 1)

% Display the results
disp('Input   |   Output (AND gate result)');
disp([testX output']);

% Check if the neural network has learned the AND gate correctly
if isequal(output', Y)
    disp('The neural network has successfully learned the AND gate.');
else
    disp('The neural network has not learned the AND gate correctly.');
end
AND GATE
20/11/2023, 9:29 pm - Arun EEC: and gate
20/11/2023, 9:29 pm - Arun EEC: % Define the input data (X) and the corresponding target output (T)
X = [0 0; 0 1; 1 0; 1 1];
T = [0; 1; 1; 1];
% Create a feedforward neural network with one hidden layer
net = feedforwardnet(4); % You can change the number of hidden neurons as needed
% Set the training parameters
net.trainParam.epochs = 1000;  % Number of training epochs
net.trainParam.goal = 1e-5;   % Training goal (MSE)
net.trainParam.showWindow = 1; % Display the training progress
% Train the neural network
net = train(net, X', T');
% Test the network with OR gate inputs
outputs = net(X');
% Display the network's responses
for i = 1:length(outputs)
    fprintf('Input: [%d, %d] -> Output: %f\n', X(i, 1), X(i, 2), outputs(i));
end
OR GATE

04/12/2023, 3:34 pm - +91 95691 15651: Syllabus for End Sem Exam  (100 marks) 
Do any five out of six. Each question will be of 20 marks.
DC to DC conversion (power circuits, working principle, waveforms and design): Buck, Boost and Buck-Boost converters. Harmonic analysis
AC to DC Conversion: Phase Controlled Converters: Principle of phase control, Single phase and three phase converter circuits with different types of loads, continuous and discontinuous conduction, effect of source inductance. Harmonic analysis
DC to AC Conversion: Single phase voltage source bridge inverters and their steady state analysis; three-phase bridge inverters with 1800 and 1200 modes; single-phase and three-phase PWM inverters.
Cyclo-converters: Principles of operation, single-phase to single-phase step-up and step-down cyclo-converters.
Drives Application of Power Electronics: Concept of electric drive and its classifications, Types of loads, Four-quadrant drive, Dynamics of motor-load combination, Steady state stability of an electric drive system, 
Control of AC and DC motors: Speed Control of AC and DC motors fed through single-phase and three-phase controlled power converter configurations, 
Regeneration and braking of AC and DC motors through static power converters.

I hope this message finds you well. I wanted to reach out and invite you to participate in an exciting event called the Cyclathon 🚴, which aims to promote the use of bicycles for short-distance commuting and create awareness about the benefits of cycling.

The Cyclathon🚴 will be held on 11th February , 2024 . It will be a fun-filled day with various activities, including a cycle march and  group rides. We believe that by encouraging more people to choose bicycles for short distances, we can contribute to a greener and healthier environment.

Your participation in the Cyclathon 🚴 would be greatly appreciated. Not only will you have a chance to enjoy a day of cycling and connect with like-minded individuals, but you will also be supporting a sustainable mode of transportation.

Together, we can make a positive impact on our community and inspire others to adopt eco-friendly commuting options.
We encourage you to bring your own cycles and join us for a day filled with fun, fitness, and camaraderie. We look forward to seeing you there and having a fantastic day of cycling.

Timings – 8:00 AM – 10:00 AM
Location - Everyone is requested to gather near Directorate Office  at 8am

EVENT WILL START AT 8.15 am

Prabh Singh

07/03/2024, 9:45 pm - Farooq: Subject: Request for Intervention Regarding Machine Learning and Techniques Course

Respected sir,

I am Umar Shaikh, a third-year student pursuing Electrical and Computer Engineering at Thapar University, writing on behalf of my entire class. We would like to bring to your attention some significant concerns regarding the Machine Learning and Techniques (ML&T) course ULC601, which is proving to be a crucial subject for our academic and placement prospects.

Issues with Dr. Alok Shukla:
Our class is grappling with challenges related to understanding the course material presented by Dr. Alok Shukla. Despite our efforts, doubts remain unresolved, and we find it challenging to comprehend the subject matter during lectures. Additionally, the lab sessions under his guidance lack meaningful practical experiences.

Attempts to seek clarification on doubts have been met with unsatisfactory responses, with students frequently directed to self-learn through external sources such as Google and YouTube. There is a noticeable lack of initiative from Dr. Shukla to engage with students and enhance our understanding of the subject.

Our lab sessions in ML&T lack sufficient exposure to practical experiments, resulting in a mere formality of submitting experiments on Google Classroom without a comprehensive grasp of the content. The objectives and basic procedures of the lab sessions are often not adequately explained, hindering our understanding.


We respectfully request a reconsideration of the faculty assigned to the ML&T course, aiming for an instructor who can effectively convey the subject matter. Additionally, we propose a change in the upcoming MST question paper and evaluation, entrusting this responsibility to an alternative faculty member.

We believe that these changes will significantly enhance the learning experience for our class, providing us with a solid foundation for both our academic pursuits and future professional challenges.

Thank you for your attention and consideration.

Sincerely,

Umar Shaikh
102119030
EEC'25

15/03/2024, 9:52 am - Priyanshu: In brief:

Calculation of all forces to obtain Fte.

Use of drive cycles and Fte to obtain power vs t graph.

Use of above graph to determine power rating of motor.

Use of above graph to determine energy consumed. ( By integration).

Use of drive cycle to determine the distance travelled ( by integration)

Use of above two values to determine the ratio (energy required)/(distance).

Multiply this ratio with desired range of vehicle to obtain the required battery capacity.
